Another document, "Atrium (heart)", states, "There are two atria in the human heart... the right atrium receives blood from the venae cavae... then contract (systole) to move blood to the ventricles." This again refers to two ventricles since the atria move blood to them. 

The "Cardiac cycle" document also mentions, "one during which the heart muscle relaxes and refills with blood, called diastole, followed by a period of robust contraction and pumping of blood, dubbed systole." While this explains the cycle, the earlier documents already confirm the number of ventricles. 

The "Heart valve" document lists the four valves but doesn't add new info on ventricles. The "Wolff–Parkinson–White syndrome" and others don't mention the count of ventricles. 

All the relevant documents consistently state there are two ventricles in the human heart. The answer should be 2.
